<DOC><DOCNO> AP880628-0186 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2107EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Floods     06-28 0317</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Floods,0333</SECOND><HEAD>27 Die In Bangladesh Flooding</HEAD><BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SYLHET, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Heavy rains and flash floods inBangladesh in the past week have killed at least 27 people anddamaged homes, crops, roads and communications, officials and newsreports said Tuesday.   Five people died Tuesday in flood-related accidents in this town92 miles northeast of Dhaka, officials reported.   Five other deaths were reported in southern Bangladesh. Earlierin the week, 17 people died nationwide.   Muzaffar Ali, his wife and five children were among the 500people evacuated from Noapara, a hilly town east of Sylhet, to arelief camp after flood waters damaged their house.   ``I am leaving the camp since water is no more there,'' saidAli, who is returning home after the floodwaters have receeded.   But government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,said the situation in other parts of the Sylhet district wasworsening because river waters were rushing in from the Indianstate of Assam.   About 1.3 million people are reported stranded in the district,they said.   In neighbouring Sunamganj district, the flooding has trapped800,000 people on the rooftops of their submerged homes, pressreports said Tuesday.   Abdur Rahim, a businessman who reached Dhaka on Tuesday fromSunamganj, said he saw thousands of people waiting on top of housesto be rescued.   A Railway Ministry official, who asked not to be identified,said train services between Dhaka and the port city of Chittagonghave been disrupted since Sunday because of incessant rains. Hesaid service on the Dhaka-Sylhet rail line was also stopped becausethe floods damaged two bridges.   The government said at least 25 people were killed in floods andrain last month, but unofficial reports claim at least 50 peoplehave died.   Hundreds of rivers run through Bangladesh, an impoverishednation of 105 million people, and flooding is common between Juneand September.</TEXT></DOC>